<section xml:id="s_matrix_grps" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Matrix groups and rigid motions</title>
<definition xml:id="d_invertible_matrix">
<title>Invertible matix</title>
<statement>
<p>
Assume either that <m>R\in \{\Z, \Q, \R, \C\}</m> or that <m>R=\Z/m\Z</m> for some <m>m\in \Z_{&gt; 0}</m>. Fix a positive integer <m>n</m>. The set of all <m>n\times n</m> matrices with coefficients in <m>R</m> is denoted <m>M_n(R)</m>. 
</p>
<p>
    Given matrices <m>A=[a_{ij}], B=[b_{ij}]\in M_n(R)</m> we define their product <m>AB</m> to be the matrix <m>C=[c_{ij}]\in M_n(R)</m>, where 
    <men xml:id="eq_matrix_mult">
        c_{ij}=\sum_{k=1}^na_{ik}b_{kj}
    </men>
    for all <m>1\leq i,j\leq n</m>.
</p>
<p>
    A matrix <m>A\in M_n(R)</m> is <term>invertible</term> if there is a matrix <m>B\in M_n(R)</m> such that 
<me>
    AB=BA=I
</me>,
where <m>I</m> is the <m>n\times n</m> identity matrix. 
</p>

<p>
    We denote by <m>\GL_n(R)</m> the set of all invertible matrices with coefficients in <m>R</m>: <ie/>, 
    <men xml:id="eq_inv_matrices_gen">
        \GL_n(R)=\{A\in M_{n}(R)\mid A \text{ is invertible}\}
    </men>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<activity xml:id="spec_matrix_grps_gen">
<title>General linear group (generalized)</title>
<statement>
<p>
Assume either that <m>R\in \{\Z, \Q, \R, \C\}</m> or that <m>R=\Z/m\Z</m> for some <m>m\in \Z_{&gt; 0}</m>. Given a positive integer <m>n</m>, the pair <m>(\GL_n(R),\cdot)</m> is a group,  where <m>\cdot</m> is matrix multiplication in <m>M_n(R)</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</activity>
<remark>
    <title>Invertible matrices and determinant</title>
<p>
    It turns out that matrix algebra in <m>M_n(R)</m> proceeds essentialy exactly as you are accustomed to, no matter how exotic our ring <m>R</m> is. In particular, we can define a determinant function 
    <md>
        <mrow>\det \colon M_n(R) \amp \rightarrow R</mrow>
        <mrow>A \amp \mapsto \det A</mrow>
    </md>
    using the usual formula, since <m>R</m> has notions of addition and multiplication. Furthermore, you can show that as usual <m>\det</m> satisfies 
    <me>
        \det AB=\det A\det B
    </me>
    for all <m>A,B\in M_n(R)</m>, and that for all <m>A\in M_n(R)</m> there is a special matrix <m>A^\dagger</m> called the <term>adjoint matrix</term> of <m>A</m> that satisfies 
    <me>
        A^\dagger A=AA^\dagger=(\det A)\, I
    </me>.
    From these observations it follows that 
    <me>
        \GL_n(R)=\{A\in M_{n}(R)\mid \det A\in R^*\}
    </me>,
    where <m>R^*</m> is the group of units of <m>R</m>, as defined in <xref ref="spec_ring_mult_groups"/> and <xref ref="spec_units_mod_n"/>. 
</p>
<p>
    Of course, that these properties of the determinant and adjoint matrix hold very much requires a proof. We will not do that here, as these will not play a fundamental role in the current course beyond making computation within these groups more convenient. However, the ring theory developed in Math 331-2 will provide a powerful general method that allows us to conclude that properties enjoyed by mathematical objects <q>defined over</q> <m>\Z</m> and <m>\C</m> are sometimes inherited by the same types of objects <q>defined over</q> a more general <m>R</m>. 
</p>  
</remark>
